column11: Republic of Korea’s Jang Kun Lee has been one of the most successful overseas raiders in VIVO Pro Kabaddi. His unique raiding style, where he merges elements of martial arts with traditional kabaddi moves, make him lethal for defenders. He has also captained the Republic of Korea’s national kabaddi team in various international events.

column11: Ajay Thakur is a true warrior who believes in fighting for victory till the end. It's this attitude that made him a perfect fit to lead Tamil Thalaivas, when they made their debut in the league. He has consistently been among the leading raiders of VIVO Pro Kabaddi since the inception. He has also been a part of a number of last-minute victories for his side and was the hero of India's 2016 Kabaddi World Cup triumph. His calm demeanour under pressure earned him the nickname 'Iceman'.

column11: ‘Captain Cool’ Anup Kumar has arguably one of the smartest kabaddi games in the current group of players. A master strategist, Kumar has not only won the VIVO Pro Kabaddi title with U Mumba in Season 2, but also led India to victory in the 2016 Kabaddi World Cup. He was the recipient of the Arjuna Award in 2012 as recognition for his immense contribution to Indian kabaddi.

column11: A gold medal winner in the 2016 Kabaddi World Cup, and one of the fittest players in VIVO Pro Kabaddi, Deepak Hooda has consistently been making his mark in the sport. After the first two seasons, he stepped up as the leading raider for Puneri Paltan in Seasons 3, 4 and 5. He also topped the Do-Or-Die raid points chart in the latter campaign indicating his ability to cope under pressure. He is one of the most capable all-rounders, and his rise has been meteoric.

column11: A stalwart in Jaipur Pink Panthers’ title win in VIVO Pro Kabaddi Season 2, Jasvir Singh is one of India’s most decorated kabaddi players. The raider from Haryana has been instrumental in India’s success in international competitions. He starred in India’s Asia Cup win in Incheon and was also part of 2016 World Cup winning squad. His leadership and personality in the locker room have earned him the nickname “Nawab.”

column11:
Having grown up in Salem, Tamil Nadu, kabaddi was second nature to Jeeva. He has been a part of Pro Kabaddi since its inception, and it’s all thanks to his training at the Nagapatnam Center of SAI. It was here that the coaches coaxed him into being a defender rather than a raider. It paid off — a gold at the Junior Nationals is a testament to that. Winning it earned him a call up for a job at the Railways, and from there he got drafted into the Pro Kabaddi caravan in 2014. He has since been in the same teams as Mohit Chhillar and Surender Nada and has forged a strong friendship with the Haryanvi duo.

Jeeva is the fourth among five siblings. His older brother plays kabaddi at the district level in Tamil Nadu. When asked if there’s any sibling rivalry in the family, he replies with an impish grin, ‘No, because my brother is better!’ In his spare time, Jeeva watches a lot of movies. Ajit Kumar and Nayantara are his favourite actors, and he plans to introduce the world of Tamil cinema to his unsuspecting teammates.

A veteran defender of the Kabaddi world, Jeeva Kumar has earned a reputation for being a master of the Super Tackle with his ability to remain calm in pressure situations and tackle raiders with minimal support. Kumar starred in U Mumba’s title winning campaign in Season 2 of VIVO Pro Kabaddi. His CV also boasts of an Asian Games gold medal that he won in Guangzhou in 2010.

He won the Best Raider Award in Season 2 for scoring 114 Raid Points in that edition. His pace and flexibility allow him to escape from both, above and below incoming defenders, which is a huge asset for him.

column11: Mahesh Goud was a consistent performer for Bengal Warriors over the course of his three-year stint with the franchise starting Season 1, scoring 96 points in 27 games. In Season 4, he won the title with Patna Pirates but could only feature in seven games. In Season 5 however, he played 21 games for U.P. Yoddha and scored 42 points.

Adjudged as the best defender in the inaugural season and then the Most Valuable Player in the following season, Manjeet Chhillar made his mark early in VIVO Pro Kabaddi. His versatile all-round skills have earned him nickname of 'One Man Army' and that was also demonstrated when he earned a gold medal at the 2016 Kabaddi World Cup. He received the Arjuna Award in 2015 for his remarkable achievements in the sport.

Skilled in both holds and dashes, Chhillar knows how to complement the other corner defender perfectly and form a successful partnership. He was one of the mainstays of the Indian team at the 2016 Kabaddi World Cup.

A joy to watch, he is fondly referred to as the 'Showman'.

column11: A master of the ‘Do-Or-Die’ raid, Rajesh Mondal won back-to-back titles with Patna Pirates in Season 3 and Season 4 of VIVO Pro Kabaddi before joining Puneri Paltan is Season 5. There he made a name for himself as well and scored the first Super 10 of his career. An employee on Eastern Railways, Mondal captured gold at the Senior National Games with the Railways team in 2011.

A player who has won the VIVO Pro Kabaddi title with the Jaipur Pink Panthers in Season 1, Rajesh Narwal is one of India’s most seasoned all-rounders. With years of experience under his belt, Narwal can easily read game situations and has developed an understanding of what his team requires from him. Narwal was among the top-scoring all-rounder in VIVO Pro Kabaddi in all of his four seasons with the Jaipur Pink Panthers.

Having played the first three seasons with Jaipur Pink Panthers, Raju is another experienced head in the Haryana Steelers dressing room. He was introduced to the game by his uncle (Mahendra Singh Dhaka’s father) about 10 years ago, and has gone on to play for the Services as well as Rajasthan as Right Corner.

Raju firmly believes in working on his game all year round. During the off-season, he runs cross-country to keep himself fit, hits the gym thrice a week, and works on his speed. He believes that his speed is main asset as a defender. Beaming with pride, he says, “I am really confident that this team will go far in the league as it has the right mix of youth and experience.”

When he is not training, he spends time with his wife and one-year-old child.

column11: A kabaddi player since his college days, Rishank Devadiga's style of play involves taking the attack to the opposition. After being picked for U Mumba in the inaugural season he went from strength to strength to become the second-most successful raider of the league in Season 3. His career is highlighted by leading the Do-Or-Die raid points tally for U Mumba in Seasons 2, 3 and 4 and for U.P. Yoddha in Season 5. After a stand-in stint as the U.P. Yoddha skipper he led Maharashtra in the 2017-18 Senior National Kabaddi Championship to win the title after 11 years.

column11: A veteran of VIVO Pro Kabaddi, Shrikant Tewthia has featured in every season of the league. The all rounder was part of the Jaipur Pink Panthers squad that made it all the way to the final of VIVO Pro Kabaddi in Season 4. A utility player, Tewthia’s all-round skills are enhanced by his experience and add stability as well as balance to the side. Skilled in Ankle Holds and Dashes, Tewthia’s tackling skills give him a particular edge in the game.

Karnataka-native Sukesh Hegde spent the first four seasons of VIVO Pro Kabaddi with Telugu Titans. He was a consistent scorer for the Titans, scoring 209 raid points in 49 matches. He got to explore his leadership ability when he was picked by Gujarat Fortunegiants as their captain for their maiden campaign in Season 5 of the league.

Surjeet comes from a village called Rindhana in Haryana where he claims nearly every young child plays kabaddi. All his siblings play the sport at various levels as well. Surjeet’s kabaddi dreams took a serious turn when he lost his elder brother, another kabaddi player on the cusp of Asian Games glory, to Cancer. It only made Surjeet more determined and at the 2014 Asian Games, he fulfilled his and his family’s collective dream to win gold wearing an India jersey.

This is Surjeet’s third season with Pro Kabaddi, having played for Dabang Delhi and Patna Pirates before this. Off-season, Surjeet is on the court for the Indian Navy and spends most of his time training in South Mumbai. He swears by yoga and meditation to keep him focused and make better split-second decisions on the mat.

Collecting 4x4 vehicles and heavy bikes keeps him occupied off the field. His open-top, restored jeep is his latest favorite.

column11: Wazir Singh leads from the front, evident from his Season 1 and 2 stints with Puneri Paltan and Season 5 performance with Haryana Steelers where he emerged as the top raider in terms of points during each of these. He stood out for Pune but then had to remain on the sidelines for the next two seasons due to injury. But he showed that he had lost none of his verve when he returned to play for Haryana in Season 5.

Sandeep Narwal started his career as a pure corner defender but has worked on his raiding over time to become a capable all-rounder. His speed and agility make him difficult to predict while he raids and his tremendous strength and grit make him a solid defender. His consistent efforts throughout VIVO Pro Kabaddi saw him become one of the few all-rounders to cross the 200-point mark in both raid points and tackle points.

column11: Surender Nada is a left-corner specialist defender with one of the most feared ankle holds in the game. He was the joint highest tackle point scorer in the inaugural season of VIVO Pro Kabaddi and instrumental in U Mumba’s title campaign in Season 2. A patient defender who can strike when least expected, Nada has even been a part of the 2016 Kabaddi World Cup winning Indian team.

Parmod is from Rindhana in Haryana, a village where almost all the kids aspire to play kabaddi at the highest levels. His tryst with the sport began when he accompanied his uncle, who used to play for CRPF, to games in and around the village. Parmod has gone on to represent the stare in U-14, U-17, U-19 national tournaments, and won two gold medals at the senior nationals.

This all rounder also represents the Railways at many national and inter-corporate tournaments, where he works as a Senior Booking Agent in Nagpur. Brought up on a protein-rich diet of milk, roti-sabzi, and yogurt, Parmod wants to leave a mark whenever he is called upon to play.
With performance that has improved season on season, Prashant Kumar Rai scored 54 points in 15 games for Telugu Titans in Season 2. He crossed 100 raid points in Season 6, finishing with 147.

Born in the Kaithal district of Haryana, Rakesh, a.k.a. ‘Rakka’, was introduced to the game by his elder brother. He started as an all rounder, but a knee injury forced him to switch to Left Cover. After spending the first three seasons with Dabang Delhi, Rakka will now don the colors of Haryana Steelers.

Off the field, Rakesh loves spending time with his family and counts on music to be his stressbuster. His teammates have mentioned Rakka’s love for Sonu Nigam’s songs.

column11: Bajirao Hodage spent the first three seasons of VIVO Pro Kabaddi with the Bengal Warriors, featuring 26 times for them. He then moved to defending champions Patna Pirates in Season 4 and helped them win their second straight VIVO Pro Kabaddi title. The Right Cover is a versatile defender who can use both, holds and dashes, to good effect as the situation demands.

He also finished the campaign as one of the top five defenders in the league that season. His first taste of VIVO Pro Kabaddi glory came with Patna Pirates in Season 5. column11:
Ashish, who hails from Panipat, is a product of the Sports Authority of India (SAI), Sonepat, Haryana. He comes from a family of sportspersons, and that also includes his bulldog, Babar. Chhokar’s elder brother plays kabaddi for local clubs back home, and their father was an ace pole-vaulter in his prime.

In his formative years, Chhokar was given a choice to pick between study and sports, with a nudge towards pole-vaulting. He chose to pursue kabaddi, but with that came its own struggles. He had to travel 15-20 kms every day to keep up with his passion. After honing his skills for two years, Ashish earned a trial at SAI, Sonepat and hasn’t looked back since.

Ashish has since added stealth to his already quick feet. His excellent raiding skills have helped him and his teammates win a Gold at the Junior Nationals, 2012. A stellar performance at the Senior Nationals for Punjab earned him a call-up for Pro Kabaddi Season 2 with the Bengaluru Bulls. An unfortunate injury meant he was forced out of the game, until now. Well rested, he is raring to go and wants to prove his mettle in the fifth season of Pro Kabaddi. What better way than to do it for the state he calls home?

Pardeep 'Record-Breaker' Narwal has fast become one of the most recognised names in the sport. This shy lad from Haryana took the kabaddi world by storm by becoming the highest point-scorer in his debut season with Patna Pirates. From then on, he has consistently broken record after record, the crowning glory of which was an 8-point raid against Haryana Steelers in Season 5 which left both players and fans speechless.

23-year old David has been playing kabaddi for three years now. He used to play football and rugby in his school in Nairobi, but when kabaddi was introduced in Kenya, his instincts told him that he would excel at the game. Through the years, he has worked on the technical side of game to complement his muscular build, agility and intelligence–all the ingredients needed to make a lethal raider.

Back home, David fine-tunes his game by watching YouTube videos of games. “I love coming to India. The opportunity to play with such gifted players and better my technique and skills is of immense help,” says David. In the World Cup that took place in Ahmedabad earlier this year, David captained his side to fifth place. He hopes that he can translate the experience that he gains every day, watching and learning from the best, on the PKL mat soon.

column11:
A Jaipur lad through and through, Mahendra was 14 when he began to play kabaddi. Before that he had harboured ambitions to play cricket for the country. While his parents were supportive, his mom didn’t take his spending the entire day playing, too kindly. His father, who played kabaddi professionally, asked Mahendra to try the sport, and even introduced him to a friend who coached boys his age.

Mahendra took to kabaddi like a moth to a flame. He has since played several national games for Rajasthan, where he caught the eye of the Services coach and landed him a job with the Indian Air Force. Being a family man, Mahendra loves juggling his time between the sport and his loved ones back home.

The only Mumbai boy in the team, Mayur’s desire to take up the sport and make it big in it comes from watching his father play for South Mumbai’s JJ Hospital's kabaddi team. Continuing his father's legacy, Mayur too turns up for tournaments in the JJ Hospital colours. How did he trump the plethora of talent that Mumbai has to offer and get selected for Pro Kabaddi? ‘It's a lot of hard work and a little bit of luck,' he answers.

Mayur's happy-go-lucky attitude has rubbed off on his peers. There’s never a dull moment around this boy. When not practicing his moves on the court, Mayur can be seen twirling his well groomed, Shikar Dhawan-esque moustache. It’s hard to miss, just like the man himself.

A farmer by occupation, Bilal began his kabaddi journey when he was 12 years old. Khadak Singh, a local coach, spotted his talent and asked Bilal to train at a mud court at the local stadium in Bijnor, Uttar Pradesh.

He has since played at regional levels and followed the Pro Kabaddi League from its inaugural season, having broken through the circuit only this year. To make his PKL debut count, Bilal has been training hard on the mat, working on his hamstrings and eating all the right things. For someone whose day begins and ends with kabaddi, Bilal is living his dream of being around senior players such as Mohit Chhillar and Surender Nada who he has been inspired by. He is raring to make an impact in whatever opportunity that is thrown at him in the coming months.

column11:
Shy when first approached, Babu is among the millenials we like — affable and confident in his abilities. He hails from Tamil Nadu and is one of the five players from Kanyakumari to play in Pro Kabaddi Season 5.

How did he embark on a journey from a town that lies on the Southern-most tip of the country to a team that has such a rich heritage in the sport? In his typical style, he answers, ‘self-interest.’ No one in his family of five plays the sport. His eagerness to succeed landed him a spot in a local kabaddi club where he sharpened his skills in raiding and defending. He relies on his speed to get out of tricky situations on the mat.

Babu trains hard and runs long distances to complement his kabaddi skills. In his spare time, this second-year student of B.Sc. Computer Science, does not prefer movies, but, if there’s Power Rangers on, he will definitely be glued to the television.

Kuldeep comes from a family of kabaddi players, his older brother Manoj Dhull too having been part of the Pro Kabaddi League. He got his first taste of the action and obsession from his eldest brother who serves in the Indian Army, after being taken to the grounds and learning the basics of the game. Manoj and Kuldeep are now returning the favour by inspiring their youngest sibling to take up the game as well.

‘Practice makes a man perfect’ is an adage Kuldeep swears by. That’s why he is rarely seen away from the mat. The only thing that can prize him away is a Salman or Katrina blockbuster.

Brimming with enthusiasm, Vikas began his journey in kabaddi under the tutelage of coach Sushil Kumar Shastri. His older brother, who plays for the Railways, was a major influence in piquing his interest in the sport. Until then, Vikas immersed himself in books. He is on course to graduate next year as a Bachelor of Arts.

Vikas was born in Rajpur, which is near Sonepat, and was brought up on a diet of desi ghee, paneer and yogurt. When he’s not training, he listens to a lot of Sufi songs, and lists Satindar Sartaj as his favourite artist.

This is Vikas’ first season in Pro Kabaddi, and he’s giving it his all in training. He says, ‘When asked to play, I want to be at my best!’

In the same season, he went on to become the fastest player to reach 50 raid points at the time. His speed allows him to surprise defenders with the Running Hand Touch and catch them off-guard while his brute strength lets him push through the defence and return to his half, making him an extremely dangerous raider.
